{"title_page": "Jangid", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe '''Jangid Brahman ''' are a [[j\u0101ti]] (sub-caste) of [[Vishwakarma]] in India, particularly [[Rajasthan]], historically known for carpenter and blackSmith , especially woodcarving and furniture making. Following [[Sanskritisation]], they were associated with the [[Brahmin]] varna. Today, the Jangid are usually known for painting<ref name=\"Joshi1976\">{{cite book|author=Om Prakash Joshi|title=Painted Folklore and Folklore Painters of India: A Study with Reference to Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xUjjBHmHMXEC&pg=PA73|year=1976|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|pages=73\u2013|id=GGKEY:1E6U03NTPRG}}</ref><ref name=\"Va\u015bish\u1e6dha1995\">{{cite book|author=R\u0101dh\u0101kr\u0325sh\u1e47a Va\u015bish\u1e6dha|title=Art and Artists of Rajasthan: A Study on the Art & Artists of Mewar with Reference to Western Indian School of Painting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kmcLLEBmPHwC&pg=PA94|year=1995|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-284-0|page=91}}</ref> and decorative works such as making seats or chariots for religious figurines.<ref name=\"Singh1998\">{{cite book|author=K. S. Singh|title=Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKsqzB4P1ioC&pg=PA201|year=1998|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-766-1|pages=201\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brahmin communities of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Artist castes]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n\nThe '''Jangid''' are a [[j\u0101ti]] (sub-caste) of [[Vishwakarma]] in India, particularly [[Rajasthan]], historically known for carpentry, especially woodcarving and furniture making. Following [[Sanskritisation]], they were associated with the [[Brahmin]] varna. Today, the Jangid are usually known for painting<ref name=\"Joshi1976\">{{cite book|author=Om Prakash Joshi|title=Painted Folklore and Folklore Painters of India: A Study with Reference to Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xUjjBHmHMXEC&pg=PA73|year=1976|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|pages=73\u2013|id=GGKEY:1E6U03NTPRG}}</ref><ref name=\"Va\u015bish\u1e6dha1995\">{{cite book|author=R\u0101dh\u0101kr\u0325sh\u1e47a Va\u015bish\u1e6dha|title=Art and Artists of Rajasthan: A Study on the Art & Artists of Mewar with Reference to Western Indian School of Painting|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kmcLLEBmPHwC&pg=PA94|year=1995|publisher=Abhinav Publications|isbn=978-81-7017-284-0|page=91}}</ref> and decorative works such as making seats or chariots for religious figurines.<ref name=\"Singh1998\">{{cite book|author=K. S. Singh|title=Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iKsqzB4P1ioC&pg=PA201|year=1998|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-766-1|pages=201\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Brahmin communities of Rajasthan]]\n[[Category:Artist castes]]\n", "name_user": "223.225.84.157", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jangid"}
{"title_page": "Mototaka Nakamura", "text_new": "{{short description|Oceanographer, meteorologist, climatologist}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr. <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n| name               = Mototaka Nakamura\n| honorific_suffix   = Sc. D\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Scientist\n| period             = \n| known_for          = Climate dynamics, Meteorology\n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = * [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology |MIT]]\n* [[North Carolina State University]] (1989)\n<!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = Characteristics of Potential Vorticity Mixing by Breaking Rossby Waves in the Vicinity of a Jet\n| thesis_url         = https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/11730\n| thesis_year        = 1994\n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = R. Alan Plumb\n| academic_advisors  = Glenn Flierl, [[Richard Lindzen]], John Marshall\n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = Meteorology <!--major academic discipline \u2013 e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist-->\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th-century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = Climate dynamics, Meteorology\n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = Climate Models are \"Mickey Mouse\"\n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Mototaka Nakamura''' is an [[Oceanography|oceanographer]] and meteorologist with background at MIT (1995 Doctor of Science in [[meteorology]]), Georgia Institute of Technology, Goddard Space Flight Centre, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Duke and Hawaii Universities, and the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology. In 2019, he wrote a short book, initially in Japanese and later translated to English, ''Confessions Of A Climate Scientist: The Global Warming Hypothesis Is An Unproven Hypothesis''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mototaka|first=Nakamura|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=9ZVOzQEACAAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEISDAE|title=Confessions of a Climate Scientist The Global Warming Hypothesis is an Unproven Hypothesis|date=2019|language=en}}</ref> \n==Research and publications==\n\nHe wrote four scientific publications affiliated with CalTech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/scientific-contributions/2012990623_Mototaka_Nakamura|title=Mototaka Nakamura's research while affiliated with California Institute of Technology and other places|last=|first=|date=|website=ResearchGate.Net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He was Visiting Associate Researcher with 12 publications while at [[University of Hawaii|International Pacific Research Center]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102152408/iprc.soest.hawaii.edu/people/nakamura.php|title=International Pacific Research Center {{!}} People {{!}} Mototaka Nakamura|date=2019-11-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nHe has authored or co-authored several books, including:\n\n* ''Destabilization of the Thermohaline Circulation by Atmospheric Feedback''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=BSNZAAAAYAAJ&q=mototaka+nakamura&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEIKjAA|title=Destabilization of the Thermohaline Circulation by Atmospheric Feedback|last2=Stone|first2=Peter H.|last3=Marotzke|first3=Jochem|date=1993|publisher=Center for Global Change Science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Characteristics of Potential Vorticity Mixing by Breaking Rossby Waves in the Vicinity of a Jet''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=PzZ9NwAACAAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEIMjAB|title=Characteristics of Potential Vorticity Mixing by Breaking Rossby Waves in the Vicinity of a Jet|date=1994|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Department of Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences|language=en}}</ref> (Sc. D Thesis<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Characteristics of potential vorticity mixing by breaking Rossby waves in the vicinity of a jet|url=https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/11730|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|date=1994|degree=Thesis|first=Mototaka|last=Nakamura}}</ref>)\n* ''Effects of Atmospheric Coupling on the Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=JSNZAAAAYAAJ&q=mototaka+nakamura&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEITjAF|title=Effects of Atmospheric Coupling on the Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation|last2=Stone|first2=Peter Hunter|last3=Marotzke|first3=Jochem|date=1994|publisher=Center for Global Change Science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis work was cited several times in ''Ocean Processes in Climate Dynamics: Global and Mediterranean Examples''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Malanotte-Rizzoli|first=P. M.|url=https://books.google.se/books?hl=sv&id=6rTvCAAAQBAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&q=nakamura#v=snippet&q=nakamura&f=false|title=Ocean Processes in Climate Dynamics: Global and Mediterranean Examples|last2=Robinson|first2=Allan R.|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-94-011-0870-6|location=|pages=87, 95, 96, 97, 108|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNakamura has authored or co-authored nearly 20 research publications that have been cited hundreds of times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&as_sdt=0,5|title=Google Scholar|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In 1994, Nakamura was co-author of a report that drew attention to \"fudge factors\" being used to make climate models appear to better match climate data.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kerr|first=Richard A.|date=1994-09-09|title=Climate Modeling's Fudge Factor Comes Under Fire|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/265/5178/1528|journal=Science|language=en|volume=265|issue=5178|pages=1528\u20131528|doi=10.1126/science.265.5178.1528|issn=0036-8075|pmid=17801523}}</ref>\n\n==Confessions of a climate scientist==\nIn September 2019, Tony Thomas, a widely published author, with many published articles on energy and environment, wrote a detailed review of the book and summarized Nakamura's background, for [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quadrant.org.au/opinion/doomed-planet/2019/09/a-climate-modeller-spills-the-beans/|title=A Climate Modeller Spills the Beans \u2013 Quadrant Online|website=quadrant.org.au|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Carolina Coast Online, News-Times, a subsidiary of [[TownNews]], published an editorial discussing the coverage of Nakamura by Thomas Lifson, the publisher of [[American Thinker]], and at [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]], and disparaging the \"global warming crisis.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927043637/https://www.carolinacoastonline.com/news_times/opinions/editorials/article_75685304-df14-11e9-8780-0fe0554a5855.html|title=Re: \u2018global warming\u2019 {{!}} Editorials {{!}} carolinacoastonline.com|date=2019-09-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn late September 2019, writing an opinion column in [[The Manila Times]], Yen Makabenta, discussed the [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]] article, and discussed several other events he argued support his opinion \"that the rejection of the climate scare is at hand.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2019/09/28/opinion/columnists/topanalysis/climate-modeler-exposes-the-lie-in-climate-change-scare/622716/|title=Climate modeler exposes the lie in climate change scare|website=The Manila Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Ferruccio Ferroni, an energy consultant with nuclear energy patents and published articles on solar energy, wrote a detailed summary of Nakamura's book, for Carnot-Cournot Network. Ferroni said Nakamura's goal for his book<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|title=Confessions of a climate scientist: The global warming hypothesis is an unproven hypothesis|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=|location=https://c-c-netzwerk.ch/images/ccn-blog_articles/717/Confessions-Nakamura.pdf|pages=}}</ref> was to renounce \"fraudulent claims\" of the \"mainstream climate science community.\" He summarized a few of Nakamura's long list of criticisms as:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-c-netzwerk.ch/klimadebatte-alarmismus-auf-grund-irrefuehrender-daten-2/|title=Klimadebatte: Alarmismus auf Grund irref\u00fchrender Daten II|last=Ferroni|first=Ferruccio|date=2019-11-20|website=Carnot-Cournot-Netzwerk|language=de-CH|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n* Models for influence of storage and transport of large amounts of energy in the seas are \u201cMickey Mouse models,\u201d because important complex phenomena cannot be included with today's computers, and these ocean phenomena are more important than the atmosphere.\n* Current computer models are not adequate for complex interactions of natural and human-caused greenhouse gases such as water vapor, carbon dioxide and radiation.\n* The hypothesis of global warming through human activity has not been proven.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Meteorologists]]\n[[Category:Climatologists]]\n\n\n{{Japan-scientist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Oceanographer, meteorologist, climatologist}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = Dr. <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n| name               = Mototaka Nakamura\n| honorific_suffix   = Sc. D\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Scientist\n| period             = \n| known_for          = Climate dynamics, Meteorology\n| home_town          =