Science in [[meteorology]]), Georgia Institute of Technology, Goddard Space Flight Centre, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, Duke and Hawaii Universities, and the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology. In 2019, he wrote a short book, initially in Japanese and later translated to English, ''Confessions Of A Climate Scientist: The Global Warming Hypothesis Is An Unproven Hypothesis''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Mototaka|first=Nakamura|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=9ZVOzQEACAAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEISDAE|title=Confessions of a Climate Scientist The Global Warming Hypothesis is an Unproven Hypothesis|date=2019|language=en}}</ref> \n==Research and publications==\n\nHe wrote four scientific publications affiliated with CalTech.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/scientific-contributions/2012990623_Mototaka_Nakamura|title=Mototaka Nakamura's research while affiliated with California Institute of Technology and other places|last=|first=|date=|website=ResearchGate.Net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He was Visiting Associate Researcher with 12 publications while at [[University of Hawaii|International Pacific Research Center]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102152408/iprc.soest.hawaii.edu/people/nakamura.php|title=International Pacific Research Center {{!}} People {{!}} Mototaka Nakamura|date=2019-11-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nHe has authored or co-authored several books, including:\n\n* ''Destabilization of the Thermohaline Circulation by Atmospheric Feedback''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=BSNZAAAAYAAJ&q=mototaka+nakamura&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEIKjAA|title=Destabilization of the Thermohaline Circulation by Atmospheric Feedback|last2=Stone|first2=Peter H.|last3=Marotzke|first3=Jochem|date=1993|publisher=Center for Global Change Science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology|language=en}}</ref>\n* ''Characteristics of Potential Vorticity Mixing by Breaking Rossby Waves in the Vicinity of a Jet''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=PzZ9NwAACAAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEIMjAB|title=Characteristics of Potential Vorticity Mixing by Breaking Rossby Waves in the Vicinity of a Jet|date=1994|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Department of Earth, Atmospheric, and Planetary Sciences|language=en}}</ref> (Sc. D Thesis<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Characteristics of potential vorticity mixing by breaking Rossby waves in the vicinity of a jet|url=https://dspace.mit.edu/handle/1721.1/11730|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|date=1994|degree=Thesis|first=Mototaka|last=Nakamura}}</ref>)\n* ''Effects of Atmospheric Coupling on the Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=JSNZAAAAYAAJ&q=mototaka+nakamura&dq=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiQnO7SpLHoAhULXpoKHe47DkwQ6AEITjAF|title=Effects of Atmospheric Coupling on the Stability of the Thermohaline Circulation|last2=Stone|first2=Peter Hunter|last3=Marotzke|first3=Jochem|date=1994|publisher=Center for Global Change Science, Massachusetts Institute of Technology|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis work was cited several times in ''Ocean Processes in Climate Dynamics: Global and Mediterranean Examples''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Malanotte-Rizzoli|first=P. M.|url=https://books.google.se/books?hl=sv&id=6rTvCAAAQBAJ&dq=mototaka+nakamura&q=nakamura#v=snippet&q=nakamura&f=false|title=Ocean Processes in Climate Dynamics: Global and Mediterranean Examples|last2=Robinson|first2=Allan R.|date=2012-12-06|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|year=|isbn=978-94-011-0870-6|location=|pages=87, 95, 96, 97, 108|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNakamura has authored or co-authored nearly 20 research publications that have been cited hundreds of times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=mototaka+nakamura&hl=en&as_sdt=0,5|title=Google Scholar|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> In 1994, Nakamura was co-author of a report that drew attention to \"fudge factors\" being used to make climate models appear to better match climate data.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kerr|first=Richard A.|date=1994-09-09|title=Climate Modeling's Fudge Factor Comes Under Fire|url=https://science.sciencemag.org/content/265/5178/1528|journal=Science|language=en|volume=265|issue=5178|pages=1528\u20131528|doi=10.1126/science.265.5178.1528|issn=0036-8075|pmid=17801523}}</ref>\n\n==Confessions of a climate scientist==\nIn September 2019, Tony Thomas, a widely published author, with many published articles on energy and environment, wrote a detailed review of the book and summarized Nakamura's background, for [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quadrant.org.au/opinion/doomed-planet/2019/09/a-climate-modeller-spills-the-beans/|title=A Climate Modeller Spills the Beans \u2013 Quadrant Online|website=quadrant.org.au|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Carolina Coast Online, News-Times, a subsidiary of [[TownNews]], published an editorial discussing the coverage of Nakamura by Thomas Lifson, the publisher of [[American Thinker]], and and at [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]], and disparaging the \"global warming crisis.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927043637/https://www.carolinacoastonline.com/news_times/opinions/editorials/article_75685304-df14-11e9-8780-0fe0554a5855.html|title=Re: \u2018global warming\u2019 {{!}} Editorials {{!}} carolinacoastonline.com|date=2019-09-27|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn late September 2019, writing an opinion column in [[The Manila Times]], Yen Makabenta, discussed the [[Quadrant (magazine)|Quadrant]] article, and discussed several other events he argued support his opinion \"that the rejection of the climate scare is at hand.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2019/09/28/opinion/columnists/topanalysis/climate-modeler-exposes-the-lie-in-climate-change-scare/622716/|title=Climate modeler exposes the lie in climate change scare|website=The Manila Times|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Ferruccio Ferroni, an energy consultant with nuclear energy patents and published articles on solar energy, wrote a detailed summary of Nakamura's book, for Carnot-Cournot Network. Ferroni said Nakamura's goal for his book<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nakamura|first=Mototaka|title=Confessions of a climate scientist: The global warming hypothesis is an unproven hypothesis|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=|location=https://c-c-netzwerk.ch/images/ccn-blog_articles/717/Confessions-Nakamura.pdf|pages=}}</ref> was to renounce \"fraudulent claims\" of the \"mainstream climate science community.\" He summarized a few of Nakamura's long list of criticisms as:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.c-c-netzwerk.ch/klimadebatte-alarmismus-auf-grund-irrefuehrender-daten-2/|title=Klimadebatte: Alarmismus auf Grund irref\u00fchrender Daten II|last=Ferroni|first=Ferruccio|date=2019-11-20|website=Carnot-Cournot-Netzwerk|language=de-CH|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n* Models for influence of storage and transport of large amounts of energy in the seas are \u201cMickey Mouse models,\u201d because important complex phenomena cannot be included with today's computers, and these ocean phenomena are more important than the atmosphere.\n* Current computer models are not adequate for complex interactions of natural and human-caused greenhouse gases such as water vapor, carbon dioxide and radiation.\n* The hypothesis of global warming through human activity has not been proven.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Oceanographers]]\n[[Category:Meteorologists]]\n[[Category:Climatologists]]\n\n\n{{Japan-scientist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mototaka_Nakamura"}
{"title_page": "Black Hebrew Israelites", "text_new": "{{short description|Black Domestic Terrorist movement}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Black Hebrews}}\n{{African American topics sidebar|right}}\n'''Black Hebrew Israelites''' (also called '''ISPUK''', '''Hebrew Israelites''', '''Black Hebrews''', '''Black Israelites''', and '''African Hebrew Israelites''') are groups of [[African Americans|Black Americans]] who [[Groups claiming affiliation with Israelites|Falsely believe that they are the descendants]] of the ancient [[Israelites]]. To varying degrees, Black Hebrew Israelite Anti-semites incorporate twisted aspects of the religious beliefs and practices of both [[Christianity]] and [[Judaism]]. Many choose to identify as Hebrew Israelites or Black Hebrews rather than [[Jews]] in order to indicate their claimed historic connections.<ref>Ben-Jochannan, p. 306.</ref><ref name=\"JVL\">{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/blackjews.html |title=The Black Jewish or Hebrew Israelite Community |accessdate=December 15, 2007 |last=Ben Levy|first=Sholomo |encyclopedia=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Johannes P. Schade |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of World Religions |title=Black Hebrews |year=2006 |publisher=Foreign Media Group |location=Franklin Park, N.J. |isbn=1-60136-000-2 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |first=Tara |last=Bahrampour |title=They're Jewish, With a Gospel Accent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/26/nyregion/they-re-jewish-with-a-gospel-accent.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 26, 2000 |accessdate=November 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBlack Supremacists \"Israelites\" are not associated with the actual Jewish community, and they do not meet the standards which are used to identify people as Jewish [[Who is a Jew?|by the Jewish community]]. The only exception to this norm is any small number of people who have formally [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]].\n\nThe Hebrew Israelite movement originated at the end of the 19th century, when [[Frank Cherry]] and [[William Saunders Crowdy]] both claimed to have received visions while on weeks long opium benders that African Americans are descendants of the [[Hebrews]] in the [[Bible]]; Cherry established the Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations in 1886 and Crowdy founded the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] in 1896.<ref name=\"Hutchinson2010\">{{cite book|last=Hutchinson|first=Dawn|title=Antiquity and Social Reform: Religious Experience in the Unification Church, Feminist Wicca and Nation of Yahweh|year=2010|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=9781443823081|page=139|quote=The first was the Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations founded by F.S. Cherry in 1886 in Chattanooga, Tennessee. Cherry preached that Adam, Eve, and Jesus were black and that African Americans lost their Hebrew identity during slavery. That only through the Eradication of Middle Eastern and European Jews could African freedom exist.  William S. Crowdy founded the Church of God and Saints of Christ in 1896 in Lawrence, Kansas. Crowdy taught that blacks were heirs of the lost tribes of Israel, while white Jews were descendants of inter-racial marriages between Israelites and white Christians.}}</ref><ref name=\"Fernheimer2014\">{{cite book|last=Fernheimer|first=Janice W.|title=Stepping Into Zion: Hatzaad Harishon, Black Jews, and the Remaking of Jewish Identity|year=2014|publisher=University of Alabama Press|isbn=9780817318246|page=10|quote=One of these groups, Prophet Cherry's Church of the Living God, the Pillar and Ground of Truth for All Nations is the oldest known Black Judaic sect. It was originally established in Chattanooga, Tennessee, in 1886. Prophet Cherry argued they were part of the original Israelite tribes chased from Babylonia (and, they claim, into Central and Western Africa where they were later sold into slavery) by the Romans in 70 CE.}}</ref><ref name=\"IVSigler2009\">{{cite book|editor-last1=Curtis IV|editor-first1=Edward E.|editor-last2=Sigler|editor-first2=Danielle Brune|title=The New Black Gods: Arthur Huff Fauset and the Study of African American Religions|year=2009|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253004086|first=Nora L.|last=Rubel|chapter='Chased Out of Palestine': Prophet Cherry's Church of God and Early Black Judaisms in the United States|page=57|quote=In 1893, Crowdy had a vision that resulted in the establishment of the Church of God and Saints in Christ.}}</ref><ref name=\"HSP1975\">{{cite journal|first=J. David|last=Bleich|title=Black Jews: A Halakhic Perspective|journal=Tradition: A Journal of Orthodox Jewish Thought|volume=15|number=1|date=Spring-Summer 1975|page=63|jstor=23258489|quote=Crowdy claimed to be the recipient of a series of revelations in which, among other things, he was told that Blacks were descendants of the ten lost tribes of Israel.}}</ref>\n\nConsequently, Black Hebrew groups were founded in the United States during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, from [[Kansas]] to [[New York City]], by both African Americans and [[West Indies|West Indian]] immigrants.<ref name=Chireau21/> In the mid-1980s, the number of Black Hebrews in the United States was between 25,000 and 40,000.<ref name=Sundquist118>Sundquist, p. 118.</ref> Black Hebrew Israelism is a non-homogenous movement with a number of groups, that have varying beliefs, practices, and relationships to Judaism and Christianity.<ref name=\"JVL\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Anti-Defamation League]] (ADL), \"Some, but not all [sects of the Black Hebrew Israelites], are outspoken anti-Semites and racists.\"<ref name=\"ADL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/black-hebrew-israelites |title=Black Hebrew Israelites |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=ADL |access-date=December 15, 2019 |quote=}}</ref> As of December 2019, the Southern Poverty Law Center \"lists 144 Black Hebrew Israelite organizations as black separatist hate groups because of their antisemitic and anti-white beliefs.\"<ref name=\"splc201912\"/>{{Context-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Overview ==\nTraditionally, many [[Black Christians]] in the [[United States]] have spiritually identified with the ancient [[Israelites]]. In the late 19th century, some of them also began to claim that they were the biological descendants of the Israelites in part due to their upbringing as Christians.<ref>Chireau, pp. 18, 21.</ref> This identification with the Israelites was a response to the sociopolitical realities of their situation in the United States, including [[Slavery in the United States|slavery]] and [[racial discrimination]].\n\nThe beliefs and practices of Black Hebrew groups vary considerably. Their differences are so great that historian [[James Tinney]] has suggested that the organizations should be divided into three groups:<ref name=Tinney/>\n* [[Black Jews]]{{dn|date=January 2020}}, who maintain a Christological perspective while adopting Jewish rituals despite not being Jewish.\n* Black Hebrews, who are more traditional in their practice of Judaism but are not Jewish.\n* Black Israelites, who are the most [[Black nationalism|nationalistic]] and the furthest from traditional Judaism.<ref name=Tinney>{{cite journal |last=Tinney |first=James |authorlink=James Tinney |date=December 7, 1973 |title=Black Jews: A House Divided |journal=[[Christianity Today]] |pages=52\u201354 }}, cited at Chireau, p. 29.</ref>\n\nBlack Hebrew organizations have certain common characteristics. [[Anthropologist]] James E. Landing, author of ''Black Judaism'', distinguishes the Black Hebrew movement, which he refers to as Black Judaism, from the normative form of Judaism that is practiced by people who are Black (\"black Judaism\"). Significantly, it does not depend on a documented lineage to Jewish ancestors nor does it require recognized [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] or [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]] conversions:\n\n{{quote|Black Judaism is ... a form of institutionalized (congregational) religious expression in which black persons identify themselves as Jews, Israelites, or Hebrews ... in a manner that seems unacceptable to the \"whites\" of the world's Jewish community, primarily because Jews take issue with the various justifications that are set forth by Black Jews in establishing this identity. Thus \"Black Judaism,\" as defined here, stands distinctly apart from \"black Judaism,\" or that Judaic expression which is found among black persons that would be acceptable to the world's Jewish community, such as conversion or birth from a recognized Jewish mother. \"Black Judaism\" has been a social movement; \"black Judaism\" has been an isolated social phenomenon.<ref name=Landing10>Landing, p. 10, quoted in Isaac, p. 520.</ref>}}\n\nLanding's definition, and its underlying assumptions about race and normative Judaism, have been criticized.{{by whom|date=March 2019}}<ref name=Isaac>Isaac, pp. 512\u2013542.</ref>\n\nThe group sometimes employs [[Open-air preaching|street preaching]] to promote their ideology. Sidewalk ministers sometimes employ provocation to advance a message that is often antisemitic, racist and xenophobic.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/11/nyregion/black-hebrew-israelites-jersey-city-suspects.html By Sarah Maslin Nir Dec. 12, 2019 The New York Times]</ref><ref>[https://apnews.com/9107f1204a15e4f5f67c8dcc9245f732 By Michael Kunzelman December 12, 2019 Associated Press]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe origins of the Black Hebrew Israelite movement are found in Frank Cherry and William Saunders Crowdy, who both claimed that they had revelations in which they believed that God told them that African Americans are descendants of the [[Hebrews]] in the [[Christian Bible]]; Cherry established the \"Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations\" in 1886 and Crowdy founded the \"[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]]\" in 1896.<ref name=\"Hutchinson2010\"/><ref name=\"Fernheimer2014\"/><ref name=\"IVSigler2009\"/><ref name=\"HSP1975\"/> The Church of God and Saints of Christ, originating in Kansas, retained elements of a messianic connection to [[Jesus]].<ref name=Chireau21>Chireau, p. 21.</ref>\n\nDuring the following decades, many more Black Hebrew congregations were established, with some holding no connection to Christianity. After World War I, for example, [[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]], an immigrant from [[Saint Kitts]], founded another Black Hebrew congregation in [[Harlem]], claiming descent from the ancient Israelites. He called it the \"[[Commandment Keepers]] of the Living God.\" <ref name=\"NYT090402\">{{cite news |first=Zev |last=Chafets |authorlink=Ze'ev Chafets |title=Obama's Rabbi |date=April 5, 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/05/magazine/05rabbi-t.html |work =[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 28, 2016 }}</ref> Similar groups selected elements of Judaism and adapted them within a structure similar to that of the [[Black church]].<ref name=Chireau21/> He incorporated it in 1930 and moved the congregation to [[Brooklyn]], where he later founded the Israelite Rabbinical Seminary, where Black Hebrew rabbis have been educated and ordained.\n\n== Groups ==\nDuring the late 19th and early 20th centuries, dozens of Black Hebrew organizations were established.<ref name=Chireau21/> In Harlem alone, at least eight such groups were founded between 1919 and 1931.<ref name=Parfitt96>Parfitt, ''Judaising Movements'', p. 96.</ref> The Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations is the oldest-known Black Hebrew group<ref name=Singer57/> and the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] is one of the largest Black Hebrew organizations.<ref name=\"Africana\"/> The Commandment Keepers, founded by Wentworth Arthur Matthew in New York, are noted for their adherence to traditional Judaism.<ref name=Moses537/> The [[African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem]] are widely known for having moved from the United States, primarily Chicago, to Israel in the late 20th century.<ref name=Shipler/><ref name=Haas/><ref name=MFA/> Other Black Hebrew groups include the [[Israelite School of Universal Practical Knowledge]], based in Philadelphia, and the [[Nation of Yahweh]], based in Miami.\n\n=== Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations ===\nThe oldest known Black Hebrew organization is the [[Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations]].<ref name=Singer57>Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", p. 57.</ref><ref name=Chireau3031>Chireau, pp. 30\u201331. \"The founding dates of the earliest black-Jewish congregations are in dispute. Shapiro notes that F.S. Cherry's Church of God was organized in Tennessee in 1886, but other sources do not confirm this date. Another group, the Moorish Zion Temple, founded in 1899 by a Rabbi Richlieu of Brooklyn, New York, was one of the earliest black Jewish congregations that did not combine Jewish and Christian beliefs, as did the Church of God and the Saints of Christ.\"</ref> The group was founded by [[Frank Cherry]] in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], Tennessee, in 1886, and it later moved to [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Singer57-58\">Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", pp. 57\u201358.</ref> Cherry, who was from the Deep South and had worked as a seaman and for the railroads before his ministry, taught himself Hebrew and [[Yiddish]].<ref>Parfitt, ''Black Jews in Africa and the Americas'', p. 88.</ref> Theologically, the Church of the Living God mixed elements of Judaism and Christianity, counting the Bible\u2014including the [[New Testament]]\u2014and the [[Talmud]] as essential scriptures.<ref name=Fauset34>Fauset, p. 34.</ref><ref name=Dorman73>Dorman, \"Black Israelites\", p. 73.</ref>\n\nThe rituals of Cherry's flock incorporated many Jewish practices and prohibitions alongside some Christian traditions.<ref name=\"Fauset36-40\">Fauset, pp. 36\u201340.</ref> For example, during prayer the men wore [[Kippah|skullcaps]] and congregants [[Mizrah|faced east]]. In addition, members of the Church were not permitted to eat [[pork]].<ref name=\"Fauset36-40\"/> Prayers were accompanied by musical instruments and [[Gospel music|gospel singing]].<ref name=\"Fauset36-37\">Fauset, pp. 36\u201337.</ref> Cherry died in 1963, when he was about 95 years old; his son, Prince Benjamin F. Cherry, succeeded him.<ref name=Dorman73/><ref name=Singer130>Singer, \"The Southern Origin of Black Judaism\", p. 130.</ref> Members of the church believed that he had temporarily left and would soon reappear in spirit in order to lead the church through his son.<ref name=Singer130/><ref name=\"Africana\">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Hudson |first=Peter |editor=[[Kwame Anthony Appiah]] |editor2=[[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia Africana|Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience]] |title=Black Jews |year=1999 |publisher=Basic Civitas Books |location=New York |page=1050 }}</ref>\n\n=== Church of God and Saints of Christ ===\n{{Main|Church of God and Saints of Christ}}\n[[File:First Tabernacle - Washington, D.C..jpg|thumb|The former headquarters of the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] The building is now known as First Tabernacle Beth El and it is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].]]\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ was established in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]], Kansas, in 1896 by African-American [[William Saunders Crowdy]].<ref name=Fox>{{cite news|url=http://www.brown.edu/Students/INDY/archives/2005-09-29/articles/arts-fox_israelite.php |title=Sons of Abraham |accessdate=June 23, 2016 |last=Fox |first=Andrew |date=September 29, 2005 |work=[[The College Hill Independent]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060310213246/http://www.brown.edu/Students/INDY/archives/2005-09-29/articles/arts-fox_israelite.php |archivedate=March 10, 2006 }}</ref> The group established its headquarters in Philadelphia in 1899, and Crowdy later relocated to Washington, D.C., in 1903. After Crowdy's death in 1908, the church continued to grow under the leadership of William Henry Plummer, who moved the organization's headquarters to its permanent location in [[Belleville, Virginia|Belleville]], Virginia, in 1921.<ref name=\"Wynia31-34\">Wynia, pp. 31\u201334.</ref>\n\nIn 1936, the Church of God and Saints of Christ had more than 200 \"tabernacles\" (congregations) and 37,000 members.<ref name=\"Africana\"/><ref name=Wynia>Wynia, n.p. <!--introduction--></ref> [[Howard Z. Plummer|Howard Zebulun Plummer]] succeeded his father and became head of the organization in 1931.<ref>Greene, p. 42.</ref> His son, Levi Solomon Plummer, became the church's leader in 1975.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rlsp/ |title=Chief Rabbi Levi S. Plummer, G.F.A. |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> The Church of God and Saints of Christ was led by Rabbi Jehu A. Crowdy, Jr., a great-grandson of William Saunders Crowdy, from 2001 until his death in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rjac/ |title=Chief Rabbi Jehu A. Crowdy, Jr., G.F.A. |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> Since 2016, it has been led by Phillip E. McNeil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rpem/ |title=Chief Rabbi Phillip E. McNeil |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> As of 2005, the church had fifty tabernacles in the United States and dozens more in Africa.<ref name=Fox/>\n\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ describes itself as \"the oldest African-American congregation in the United States that adheres to the tenets of Judaism\".<ref name=Chireau3031/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cogasoc.org/main.html |title=Church of God and Saints of Christ |accessdate=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080130002542/http://www.cogasoc.org/main.html |archivedate=January 30, 2008  }}</ref> Founded by American [[William Saunders Crowdy]] in Kansas in 1896, it teaches that all Jews were originally black, and that African Americans are descendants of the [[Ten Lost Tribes|lost tribes of Israel]].<ref name=Kidd>Kidd, p. 59.</ref><ref name=Singer59>Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", p. 59.</ref> Members believe that [[Jesus]] was neither God nor the son of God, but rather an adherent of Judaism and a [[prophet]]. They also consider William Saunders Crowdy, their founder in Kansas, to be a prophet.<ref name=\"gallagher\">Gallagher, p. 146.</ref>\n\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ synthesizes rituals from both Judaism and Christianity. They have adopted rites drawn from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]]s. Its Old Testament observances include the use of the [[Hebrew calendar|Jewish calendar]], the celebration of [[Passover]], the [[Brit milah|circumcision]] of infant males, the commemoration of the [[Shabbat|Sabbath]] on [[Saturday]], and the wearing of [[Kippah|yarmulkes]]. Its New Testament rites include [[baptism]] (immersion) and [[footwashing]], both of which have Old Testament origins.<ref name=Kidd/><ref name=Singer59/>\n\n=== Commandment Keepers ===\n{{Main|Commandment Keepers}}\n[[File:RabbiMatthewHoldingTorah.jpg|thumb|The founder of the Commandment Keepers, [[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]] holding a [[Sefer Torah]].]]\n[[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]] founded the Commandment Keepers Congregation in Harlem in 1919.<ref name=\"JVL\"/> Matthew was influenced by the non-black Jews he met as well as by [[Marcus Garvey]] and the [[Universal Negro Improvement Association and African Communities League]]. Garvey used the Biblical Jews in exile as a metaphor for [[black people]] in North America. One of the accomplishments of Garvey's movement was to strengthen the connection between black Americans and Africa, Ethiopia in particular. When Matthew later learned about the [[Beta Israel]]\u2014Ethiopian Jews\u2014he identified with them.<ref name=Chireau25>Chireau, p. 25.</ref>\n\nToday the Commandment Keepers follow traditional Jewish practices and observe [[Jewish holidays]].<ref name=Moses537>Moses, p. 537.</ref> Members observe [[kashrut]], circumcise newborn boys and celebrate [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah]]s, and their [[synagogue]] has a [[mechitza]] to separate men and women during worship.<ref name=\"Jewish Week\">{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Herschthal |title=Decline Of A Black Synagogue |url=http://joi.org/bloglinks/black%20synagogue%20Jewish%20Week.htm |work=[[The Jewish Week]] |date=July 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130112220712/http://joi.org/bloglinks/black%20synagogue%20Jewish%20Week.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nThe Commandment Keepers believe that they are descendants of [[Solomon]] and the [[Queen of Sheba]].<ref name=Parfitt95>Parfitt, ''Judaising Movements'', p. 95.</ref> Matthew taught that \"the Black man is a Jew\" and \"all genuine Jews are Black men\",<ref name=Sundquist116>Sundquist, p. 116.</ref> but he valued non-black Jews as those who had preserved Judaism over the centuries.<ref name=\"JVL\"/> Matthew maintained cordial ties with non-black Jewish leaders in New York and frequently invited them to worship at his synagogue.<ref name=Wolfson48>Wolfson, p. 48.</ref>\n\nMatthew established the Ethiopian Hebrew Rabbinical College (later renamed the Israelite Rabbinical Academy) in Brooklyn. He ordained more than 20 [[rabbi]]s, who went on to lead congregations throughout the United States and the Caribbean.<ref name=Sundquist116/><ref name=Wolfson48/> He remained the leader of the Commandment Keepers in Harlem, and in 1962 the congregation moved to a landmark building on 123rd Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc-architecture.com/HAR/HAR025.htm |title=Commandment Keepers Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation |accessdate=February 1, 2008 |publisher=New York Architecture }}</ref>\n\nMatthew died in 1973, sparking an internal conflict over who would succeed him as head of the Harlem congregation. Shortly before his death, Matthew named his grandson, David Matthew Dor\u00e9, as the new spiritual leader. Dor\u00e9 was 16 years old at the time. In 1975, the synagogue's board elected Rabbi Willie White to be its leader. Rabbi Dor\u00e9 occasionally conducted services at the synagogue until the early 1980s, when White had Dor\u00e9 and some other members locked out of the building. Membership declined throughout the 1990s and by 2004, only a few dozen people belonged to the synagogue. In 2007 the Commandment Keepers sold the building, while various factions among former members sued one another.<ref name=\"Jewish Week\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackjews.org/Essays/DestructionofCommandmentKeepers.html |title=The Destruction of Commandment Keepers, Inc. 1919\u20132007 |accessdate=February 10, 2008 |last=Ben Levy |first=Sholomo |work=BlackJews.org |publisher=International Israelite Board of Rabbis }}</ref>\n\nBesides the Harlem group, there are eight or ten Commandment Keeper congregations in the New York area, and others exist throughout North America as well as in [[Israel]].<ref>Goldschmidt, p. 221.</ref> Since 2000, seven rabbis have graduated from the Israelite Rabbinical Academy founded by Matthew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackjews.org/IsraeliteAcademy.html |title=Israelite Academy |accessdate=February 10, 2008 |work=BlackJews.org |publisher=International Israelite Board of Rabbis }}</ref>\n\n=== African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem ===\n{{Main|African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem}}\n[[File:Black hebrews Dimona visit1.jpg|thumb|African Hebrew Israelites speak to visitors in [[Dimona]], Israel.]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 32040 Africans Hebrew Israelites in Dimona.JPG|thumb|A sign in [[Dimona]].]]\n[[Ben Ammi Ben-Israel]] established the African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], in 1966, at a time when [[black nationalism]] was on the rise as a response to the [[Civil Rights Movement]]. In 1969, after a sojourn in [[Liberia]], Ben Ammi and about 30 Hebrew Israelites moved to [[Israel]].<ref name=Haas>{{cite news |last=Haas |first=Danielle |title=Black Hebrews fight for citizenship in Israel |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2002/11/15/MN144395.DTL |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=November 15, 2002 |accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref> Over the next 20 years, nearly 600 more members left the United States for Israel. As of 2006, about 2,500 Hebrew Israelites live in [[Dimona]] and two other towns in the [[Negev]] region of Israel, where they are widely referred to as Black Hebrews.<ref name=CBS>{{cite news |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Music Earns Black Hebrews Some Acceptance |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/05/ap/world/mainD8GPUNGG8.shtml |work=[[CBS News]] |date=April 5, 2006 |accessdate=May 25, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060507212849/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/05/ap/world/mainD8GPUNGG8.shtml |archivedate = May 7, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition, there are Hebrew Israelite communities in several major American cities, including Chicago, St. Louis, and Washington, D.C.<ref name=Michaeli75>Michaeli, p. 75.</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrews believe they are descended from members of the [[Tribe of Judah]] who were exiled from the [[Land of Israel]] after the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] destroyed the [[Second Temple]] in 70 CE.<ref name=CBS/><ref name=OurStory>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingdomofyah.com/our_story.htm |title=Our Story |accessdate=May 25, 2008 |publisher=The African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem }}</ref> The group incorporates elements of [[African-American culture]] into their interpretation of the Bible.<ref name=Michaeli75/> They do not recognize rabbinical Jewish interpretations such as the [[Talmud]].<ref name=CBS/> The Black Hebrews observe [[Shabbat]] and biblically ordained [[Jewish holidays]] such as [[Yom Kippur]] and [[Passover]].<ref name=Michaeli76>Michaeli, p. 76.</ref>\n\nMen wear ''[[tzitzit]]'' on their African print shirts, women follow the [[niddah]] (biblical laws concerning menstruation),<ref name=Michaeli75/> and newborn boys are circumcised.<ref name=Haas/> In accordance with their interpretation of the Bible, the Black Hebrews follow a strictly [[veganism|vegan diet]] and only wear [[natural fabric]]s.<ref name=Haas/><ref name=OurStory/> Most men have [[Polygyny|more than one wife]], and [[birth control]] is not permitted.<ref name=CBS/>\n\nWhen the first Black Hebrews arrived in Israel in 1969, they claimed citizenship under the [[Law of Return]], which gives eligible Jews immediate citizenship.<ref>Michaeli, pp. 73\u201374.</ref> The Israeli government ruled in 1973 that the group did not qualify for automatic citizenship because they could not prove Jewish descent and had not undergone Orthodox conversion. The Black Hebrews were denied [[work permit]]s and state benefits. The group accused the Israeli government of [[racism|racist discrimination]].<ref name=Michaeli74>Michaeli, p. 74.</ref> In 1981, a group of American civil rights activists led by [[Bayard Rustin]] investigated and concluded that racism was not the cause of the Black Hebrews' situation.<ref name=Shipler>{{cite news |last=Shipler |first=David K. |title=Israelis Urged To Act Over Black Hebrew Cult |url=https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F4071FFA395F0C738FDDA80894D9484D81 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 30, 1981 |accessdate=May 28, 2008 }}</ref> No official action was taken to return the Black Hebrews to the United States, but some individual members were [[Deportation|deported]] for working illegally.<ref name=Michaeli74/>\n\nSome Black Hebrews [[relinquishment of United States nationality|renounced their American citizenship]] in order to try to prevent more deportations. In 1990, Illinois legislators helped negotiate an agreement that resolved the Black Hebrews' legal status in Israel. Members of the group are permitted to work and they also have access to housing and social services. The Black Hebrews reclaimed their American citizenship and have received aid from the U.S. government, which helped them build a school and additional housing.<ref name=Michaeli74/> In 2003 the agreement was revised, and the Black Hebrews were granted [[permanent residency]] in Israel.<ref name=MFA>{{cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/AboutIsrael/People/Pages/The%20Black%20Hebrews.aspx |title=The Hebrew Israelite Community |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |date=September 29, 2006 |publisher=Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs }}</ref><ref name=Kaufman>{{cite news |last=Kaufman |first=David |title=Quest for a Homeland Gains a World Stage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/16/fashion/sundaystyles/16BUTLER.html |work=The New York Times|date=April 16, 2006 |accessdate=May 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Elyakim Ben-Israel became the first Black Hebrew to gain Israeli citizenship. The Israeli government said that more Black Hebrews may be granted citizenship.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alush |first=Zvi |title=First Black Hebrew Gets Israeli Citizenship |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3665976,00.html |work=[[Ynetnews]] |date=February 2, 2009 |accessdate=February 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrews of Israel maintain a [[gospel music|gospel choir]], which tours throughout Israel and the United States. The group owns restaurants in several Israeli cities.<ref name=Michaeli74/> In 2003 the Black Hebrews garnered public attention when singer [[Whitney Houston]] visited them in Dimona.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel retreat for Houston |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2940042.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=May 27, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Whitney Houston visits Israel for Christmas album inspiration |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-05-27-houston-israel_x.htm |work=USA Today|date=May 28, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Palti |first=Michal |title=Whitney does Dimona |url=http://www.culteducation.com/reference/black_hebrews/black_hebrews6.html |work=[[Haaretz]] |date=May 29, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref> In 2006, [[Eddie Butler (singer)|Eddie Butler]], a Black Hebrew, was chosen by the Israeli public to [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest 2006|represent Israel]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006|Eurovision Song Contest]].<ref name=CBS/><ref name=Kaufman/>\n\n== Extremist fringe ==\nIn late 2008, the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) wrote that \"the extremist fringe of the Hebrew Israelite movement\" is [[Black supremacy|black supremacist]]. It also wrote that the members of such groups \"believe that [[Jews]] are devilish impostors and ... openly condemn [[White people|whites]] as [[evil]] personified, deserving only death or slavery\". The SPLC also wrote that \"most Hebrew Israelites are neither explicitly racist nor [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] and do not advocate violence\".<ref name=Ready>{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2008/racist-black-hebrew-israelites-becoming-more-militant |title=Racist Black Hebrew Israelites Becoming More Militant |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |date=Fall 2008 |work=Intelligence Report |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center }}</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrew groups which are characterized as black supremacist by the SPLC include the [[Israelite School of Universal Practical Knowledge]],<ref name=\"god_and_general\">{{cite news|url=http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=948|title=God and the General. Leader Discusses Black Supremacist Group|date=Fall 2008|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|accessdate=September 8, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907052245/http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=948|archive-date=September 7, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[Nation of Yahweh]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2001/winter/popularity-and-populism |title=Popularity and Populism |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |first=Martin A. |last=Lee |date=Winter 2001 |work=Intelligence Report |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center}}</ref> and the [[Israelite Church of God in Jesus Christ]].<ref name=Ready/> Also, the [[Anti-Defamation League]] has written that the \"12 Tribes of Israel\" website, which is maintained by a Black Hebrew group, promotes black supremacy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.adl.org/poisoning_web/black_bigots.html |title=Poisoning the Web: Hatred Online \u2013 African-American Anti-Semitism |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |year=2001 |publisher=Anti-Defamation League|url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102103308/http://archive.adl.org/poisoning_web/black_bigots.html |archivedate=January 2, 2014  }}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, the Southern Poverty Law Center \"lists 144 Black Hebrew Israelite organizations as black separatist hate groups because of their antisemitic and anti-white beliefs.\"<ref name=\"splc201912\">{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/12/12/suspects-jersey-city-attack-expressed-interest-black-hebrew-israelites-authorities-say |title=Suspects in Jersey City Attack 'Expressed Interest' in Black Hebrew Israelites, Authorities Say |last= |first= |date=December 12, 2019 |website= |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>{{Context-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\nA 1999 [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] [[Project Megiddo|terrorism risk assessment report]] stated that \"violent radical fringe members\" of the Black Hebrew Israelite movement hold \"beliefs [that] bear a striking resemblance to the [[Christian Identity]] theology practiced by many [[White supremacy|white supremacists]].\"<ref name=Megidddo>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbi.gov:80/library/megiddo/publicmegiddo.pdf |title=Project Megiddo |date=1999 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000815061728/http://www.fbi.gov/library/megiddo/publicmegiddo.pdf |pages=23\u201325 |archivedate=August 15, 2000 |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nacos2015\">{{cite book |last=Nacos |first=Brigitte L. |title=Terrorism and Counterterrorism |year=2015 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=9781317343646 |page=79}}</ref> It also wrote that \"the overwhelming majority of [Black Hebrew Israelites] are unlikely to engage in violence.\"<ref name=Megidddo/>\n\nOn December 10, 2019, two people who had expressed interest in the Black Hebrew Israelite movement, were killed in a [[2019 Jersey City shooting|shootout with police]] after killing a police detective at [[Bayview \u2013 New York Bay Cemetery|Bayview Cemetery]] and three people at the JC Kosher Supermarket in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], New Jersey; the Jewish co-owner of the grocery store, an employee, and a Jewish shopper. Authorities treated the incident as an act of [[Domestic terrorism in the United States|domestic terrorism]].<ref name=WaPoJersey>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/15/probe-jersey-city-shooting-leads-fbi-arrest-pawn-shop-owner-weapons-charges/|title=Probe of Jersey City shooting leads FBI to arrest pawn shop owner on weapons charge|author=Derek Hawkins|work=The Washington Post|date=December 15, 2019}}</ref> [[Capers Funnye]], who has been the [[rabbi]] for the past 26 years of the 200-member [[Beth Shalom B'nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/05/magazine/05rabbi-t.html?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=8160E532FBE361FE2D084D04F6C16C31&gwt=pay&assetType=REGIWALL By Zev Chafets for the New York Times, Barack Obama's Rabbi - Capers Funnye - Profile \"Funnye, the chief rabbi of the Beth Shalom B\u2019nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation in Chicago\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/commentary/ct-opinion-anti-semitism-rabbi-funnye-black-hebrew-israelites-20191213-mjv6q5azvrf63pyuqpkqalhc2i-story.html By Julia Lieblich for the Chicago Tribune Dec. 13, 2019 \"Commentary: Rabbi Capers Funnye, other Black Hebrew Israelites wrongly connected to Jersey City shooters\", \"'I felt terrible that innocent lives were taken first and foremost,' said Funnye, rabbi for 26 years of the 200-member Beth Shalom B\u2019nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation of Chicago, a member of the Chicago Board of Rabbis and the chief rabbi of the International Israelite Board of Rabbis.\"]</ref> condemned the attack and said that his community was \"gripped by sadness\" over \"the heinous actions of two disturbed individuals who cloaked themselves in anti-Semitism and hate-filled rhetoric\". He also criticized the media reports by saying that it was \"unfortunate that the media uses the term \u2018Black Hebrew Israelites\u2019 without distinction as if the description is a one size fits all and it is absolutely not!\" Funnye emphasized that \"we don\u2019t want to be seen as some radical fringe group with a false narrative because we are black and profess Judaism; we are Torah-oriented Jews.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/black-hebrew-israelite-leader-condemns-heinous-jersey-city-shooting/|title=Black Hebrew Israelite leader condemns \u2018heinous\u2019 Jersey City shooting|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2019, a man with a [[machete]] [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|attacked several Orthodox Jewish people]] during [[Hanukkah]] celebrations in a house in [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]], New York. Authorities revealed the fact that his journals included what appeared to be a reference to Black Hebrew Israelites stating that \"Hebrew Israelites\" have taken from \"ebinoid Israelites\".<ref name=WaPoNY>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/30/monsey-stabbing-grafton-thomas-suspect/|title=Hanukkah stabbing suspect searched \u2018why did Hitler hate the Jews,\u2019 prosecutors say|date=December 30, 2019|author=Shayna Jacobs, Deanna Paul, Maria Sacchetti and Hannah Knowles|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of theological and historical claims ==\nAfrican American [[Christian apologetics]] organizations, such as the Jude 3 Project, have critiqued the theological and historical claims presented by various Black Hebrew Israelite sects.<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Morgan |title=The Hebrew Israelites in That March for Life Viral Video, Explained |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2019/january-web-only/hebrew-israelites-urban-apologetics-covington-march-life.html |publisher=[[Christianity Today]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |language=English |date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[African American\u2013Jewish relations]]\n* [[Afro-American religion]]\n* [[Groups claiming affiliation with Israelites]]\n** [[British Israelism]]\n** [[Christian Identity]]\n** [[French Israelism]]\n** [[Nordic Israelism]]\n* [[Messianic Judaism]]\n* [[Moorish Science Temple of America]]\n* [[Religion in Black America]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ben-Jochannan |first=Yosef A.A. |authorlink=Yosef Ben-Jochannan |title=We, the Black Jews: Witness to the \"White Jewish Race\" Myth |origyear=1983 |year=1993 |publisher=Black Classic Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=0-933121-40-7 }}\n*{{cite book |first1=Edith |last1=Bruder |authorlink1=Edith Bruder |first2=Tudor |last2=Parfitt |authorlink2=Tudor Parfitt |editor=Edith Bruder |editor2=Tudor Parfitt |title=African Zion: Studies in Black Judaism |year=2012 |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |isbn=978-1-4438-3802-3 |chapter=Introduction |chapterurl=http://www.cambridgescholars.com/download/sample/57725 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Chireau |first=Yvonne |editor=Yvonne Patricia Chireau |editor2=[[Nathaniel Deutsch]] |title=Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-511257-1 |chapter=Black Culture and Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism, 1790\u20131930, an Overview |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195112580 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last1=Gallagher |editor-first1=Eugene V. |editor-last2=Ashcraft |editor-first2=W. Michael |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America |volume=1 |year=2006 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Conn. |isbn=0-275-98713-2 |last=Dorman |first=Jacob S. |chapter=Black Israelites }}\n* {{cite book |last=Fauset |first=Arthur Huff |authorlink=Arthur Fauset |title=Black Gods of the Metropolis: Negro Religious Cults of the Urban North |origyear=1944 |year=2002 |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |location=Philadelphia |isbn=0-8122-1001-8 }}\n* {{cite book |title=The New Religious Movements Experience in America |last=Gallagher |first=Eugene V. |year=2004 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Conn. |isbn=0-313-32807-2 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Goldschmidt |first=Henry |title=Race and Religion Among the Chosen Peoples of Crown Heights |year=2006 |publisher=Rutgers University Press |location=New Brunswick, N.J. |isbn=0-8135-3897-1 }}\n* {{cite book |title=Selling Black History for Carter G. Woodson: A Diary, 1930\u20131933 |last=Greene |first=Lorenzo Johnston |authorlink=Lorenzo Greene |editor=Arvarh E. Strickland |year=1996 |publisher=University of Missouri Press |location=Columbia |isbn=0-8262-1068-6 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Isaac |first=Walter |editor=[[Lewis Gordon|Lewis R. Gordon]] |editor2=Jane Anna Gordon |title=A Companion to African-American Studies |year=2006 |publisher=Blackwell Publishing |location=Malden, Mass. |isbn=0-631-23516-7 |chapter=Locating African-American Judaism: A Critique of White Normativity }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Forging of Races: Race and Scripture in the Protestant Atlantic World, 1600-2000 |last=Kidd |first=Colin |authorlink=Colin Kidd |year=2006 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-79324-6 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Landing |first=James E. |title=Black Judaism: Story of an American Movement |year=2002 |publisher=Carolina Academic Press |location=Durham, N.C. |isbn=0-89089-820-0 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Michaeli |first=Ethan |editor=Yvonne Patricia Chireau |editor2=[[Nathaniel Deutsch]] |title=Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-511257-1 |chapter=Another Exodus: The Hebrew Israelites from Chicago to Dimona |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195112580 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Moses |first=Wilson Jeremiah |editor=[[Cornel West]] |editor2=Eddie S. Glaude, Jr. |title=African American Religious Thought: An Anthology |year=2003 |publisher=Westminster John Knox Press |location=Louisville, Ky. |isbn=0-664-22459-8 |chapter=Chosen Peoples of the Metropolis: Black Muslims, Black Jews, and Others |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780664224592 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Parfitt |first=Tudor |title=Black Jews in Africa and the Americas |year=2013 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge, Mass. |isbn=0-674-07150-6 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Parfitt |first=Tudor |author2=Emanuela Trevisan Semi |title=Judaising Movements: Studies in the Margins of Judaism in Modern Times |year=2002 |publisher=Routledge |location=New York |isbn=0-7007-1515-0 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last1=Baer |editor-first1=Hans A. |editor-last2=Jones |editor-first2=Yvonne |title=African Americans in the South: Issues of Race, Class, and Gender |year=1992 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |location=Athens, Ga. |isbn=0-8203-1376-9 |last=Singer |first=Merrill |chapter=The Southern Origin of Black Judaism |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780820313771 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Singer |first=Merrill |editor=Yvonne Patricia Chireau |editor2=[[Nathaniel Deutsch]] |title=Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-511257-1 |chapter=Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect: The Black Hebrew Israelites |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195112580 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Sundquist |first=Eric J. |title=Strangers in the Land: Blacks, Jews, Post-Holocaust America |year=2002 |publisher=Harvard University Press |location=Cambridge, Mass. |isbn=0-674-01942-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/strangersinlandb00sund }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wolfson |first=Bernard J. |editor=Yvonne Patricia Chireau |editor2=[[Nathaniel Deutsch]] |title=Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-511257-1 |chapter=African American Jews: Dispelling Myths, Bridging the Divide |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195112580 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Wynia |first=Elly M. |title=The Church of God and Saints of Christ: The Rise of Black Jews |year=1994 |publisher=Routledge |location=New York |isbn=0-8153-1136-2 }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book|author=Jacob S. Dorman|title=Chosen People: The Rise of American Black Israelite Religions|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbgQSgyARRgC|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-530140-3}}\n*{{cite book|author=Martina K\u00f6nighofer|title=The New Ship of Zion: Dynamic Diaspora Dimensions of the African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-YEcgmaAdAC&|year=2008|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=978-3-8258-1055-9}}\n*{{cite news\n| url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2011-03-30/news/black-hebrew-israelites-new-york-s-most-obnoxious-prophets/\n| title=Black Hebrew Israelites: New York's Most Obnoxious Prophets\n| author=[[Steven Thrasher]]\n| date=March 30, 2011\n| newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:1886 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1886]]\n[[Category:Black Hebrew Israelites| ]]\n[[Category:Groups claiming Israelite descent]]\n[[Category:African and Black nationalism]]\n[[Category:Monotheistic religions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Black American movement}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Black Hebrews}}\n{{African American topics sidebar|right}}\n'''Black Hebrew Israelites''' (also called '''Hebrew Israelites''', '''Black Hebrews''', '''Black Israelites''', and '''African Hebrew Israelites''') are groups of [[African Americans|Black Americans]] who [[Groups claiming affiliation with Israelites|believe that they are the descendants]] of the ancient [[Israelites]]. To varying degrees, Black Hebrew Israelites incorporate certain aspects of the religious beliefs and practices of both [[Christianity]] and [[Judaism]]. Many choose to identify as Hebrew Israelites or Black Hebrews rather than [[Jews]] in order to indicate their claimed historic connections.<ref>Ben-Jochannan, p. 306.</ref><ref name=\"JVL\">{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/Judaism/blackjews.html |title=The Black Jewish or Hebrew Israelite Community |accessdate=December 15, 2007 |last=Ben Levy|first=Sholomo |encyclopedia=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor=Johannes P. Schade |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of World Religions |title=Black Hebrews |year=2006 |publisher=Foreign Media Group |location=Franklin Park, N.J. |isbn=1-60136-000-2 }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |first=Tara |last=Bahrampour |title=They're Jewish, With a Gospel Accent |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/06/26/nyregion/they-re-jewish-with-a-gospel-accent.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 26, 2000 |accessdate=November 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBlack Hebrew Israelites are not associated with the mainstream Jewish community, and they do not meet the standards which are used to identify people as Jewish [[Who is a Jew?|by the Jewish community]]. The only exception to this norm is any small number of people who have formally [[Conversion to Judaism|converted to Judaism]].\n\nThe Hebrew Israelite movement originated at the end of the 19th century, when [[Frank Cherry]] and [[William Saunders Crowdy]] both claimed to have received visions that African Americans are descendants of the [[Hebrews]] in the [[Bible]]; Cherry established the Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations in 1886 and Crowdy founded the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] in 1896.<ref name=\"Hutchinson2010\">{{cite book|last=Hutchinson|first=Dawn|title=Antiquity and Social Reform: Religious Experience in the Unification Church, Feminist Wicca and Nation of Yahweh|year=2010|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=9781443823081|page=139|quote=The first was the Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations founded by F.S. Cherry in 1886 in Chattanooga, Tennessee. Cherry preached that Adam, Eve, and Jesus were black and that African Americans lost their Hebrew identity during slavery. Later, William S. Crowdy founded the Church of God and Saints of Christ in 1896 in Lawrence, Kansas. Crowdy taught that blacks were heirs of the lost tribes of Israel, while white Jews were descendants of inter-racial marriages between Israelites and white Christians.}}</ref><ref name=\"Fernheimer2014\">{{cite book|last=Fernheimer|first=Janice W.|title=Stepping Into Zion: Hatzaad Harishon, Black Jews, and the Remaking of Jewish Identity|year=2014|publisher=University of Alabama Press|isbn=9780817318246|page=10|quote=One of these groups, Prophet Cherry's Church of the Living God, the Pillar and Ground of Truth for All Nations is the oldest known Black Judaic sect. It was originally established in Chattanooga, Tennessee, in 1886. Prophet Cherry argued they were part of the original Israelite tribes chased from Babylonia (and, they claim, into Central and Western Africa where they were later sold into slavery) by the Romans in 70 CE.}}</ref><ref name=\"IVSigler2009\">{{cite book|editor-last1=Curtis IV|editor-first1=Edward E.|editor-last2=Sigler|editor-first2=Danielle Brune|title=The New Black Gods: Arthur Huff Fauset and the Study of African American Religions|year=2009|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253004086|first=Nora L.|last=Rubel|chapter='Chased Out of Palestine': Prophet Cherry's Church of God and Early Black Judaisms in the United States|page=57|quote=In 1893, Crowdy had a vision that resulted in the establishment of the Church of God and Saints in Christ.}}</ref><ref name=\"HSP1975\">{{cite journal|first=J. David|last=Bleich|title=Black Jews: A Halakhic Perspective|journal=Tradition: A Journal of Orthodox Jewish Thought|volume=15|number=1|date=Spring-Summer 1975|page=63|jstor=23258489|quote=Crowdy claimed to be the recipient of a series of revelations in which, among other things, he was told that Blacks were descendants of the ten lost tribes of Israel.}}</ref>\n\nConsequently, Black Hebrew groups were founded in the United States during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, from [[Kansas]] to [[New York City]], by both African Americans and [[West Indies|West Indian]] immigrants.<ref name=Chireau21/> In the mid-1980s, the number of Black Hebrews in the United States was between 25,000 and 40,000.<ref name=Sundquist118>Sundquist, p. 118.</ref> Black Hebrew Israelism is a non-homogenous movement with a number of groups, that have varying beliefs, practices, and relationships to Judaism and Christianity.<ref name=\"JVL\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Anti-Defamation League]] (ADL), \"Some, but not all [sects of the Black Hebrew Israelites], are outspoken anti-Semites and racists.\"<ref name=\"ADL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/black-hebrew-israelites |title=Black Hebrew Israelites |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=ADL |access-date=December 15, 2019 |quote=}}</ref> As of December 2019, the Southern Poverty Law Center \"lists 144 Black Hebrew Israelite organizations as black separatist hate groups because of their antisemitic and anti-white beliefs.\"<ref name=\"splc201912\"/>{{Context-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Overview ==\nTraditionally, many [[Black Christians]] in the [[United States]] have spiritually identified with the ancient [[Israelites]]. In the late 19th century, some of them also began to claim that they were the biological descendants of the Israelites in part due to their upbringing as Christians.<ref>Chireau, pp. 18, 21.</ref> This identification with the Israelites was a response to the sociopolitical realities of their situation in the United States, including [[Slavery in the United States|slavery]] and [[racial discrimination]].\n\nThe beliefs and practices of Black Hebrew groups vary considerably. Their differences are so great that historian [[James Tinney]] has suggested that the organizations should be divided into three groups:<ref name=Tinney/>\n* [[Black Jews]]{{dn|date=January 2020}}, who maintain a Christological perspective while adopting Jewish rituals despite not being Jewish.\n* Black Hebrews, who are more traditional in their practice of Judaism but are not Jewish.\n* Black Israelites, who are the most [[Black nationalism|nationalistic]] and the furthest from traditional Judaism.<ref name=Tinney>{{cite journal |last=Tinney |first=James |authorlink=James Tinney |date=December 7, 1973 |title=Black Jews: A House Divided |journal=[[Christianity Today]] |pages=52\u201354 }}, cited at Chireau, p. 29.</ref>\n\nBlack Hebrew organizations have certain common characteristics. [[Anthropologist]] James E. Landing, author of ''Black Judaism'', distinguishes the Black Hebrew movement, which he refers to as Black Judaism, from the normative form of Judaism that is practiced by people who are Black (\"black Judaism\"). Significantly, it does not depend on a documented lineage to Jewish ancestors nor does it require recognized [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] or [[Conservative Judaism|Conservative]] conversions:\n\n{{quote|Black Judaism is ... a form of institutionalized (congregational) religious expression in which black persons identify themselves as Jews, Israelites, or Hebrews ... in a manner that seems unacceptable to the \"whites\" of the world's Jewish community, primarily because Jews take issue with the various justifications that are set forth by Black Jews in establishing this identity. Thus \"Black Judaism,\" as defined here, stands distinctly apart from \"black Judaism,\" or that Judaic expression which is found among black persons that would be acceptable to the world's Jewish community, such as conversion or birth from a recognized Jewish mother. \"Black Judaism\" has been a social movement; \"black Judaism\" has been an isolated social phenomenon.<ref name=Landing10>Landing, p. 10, quoted in Isaac, p. 520.</ref>}}\n\nLanding's definition, and its underlying assumptions about race and normative Judaism, have been criticized.{{by whom|date=March 2019}}<ref name=Isaac>Isaac, pp. 512\u2013542.</ref>\n\nThe group sometimes employs [[Open-air preaching|street preaching]] to promote their ideology. Sidewalk ministers sometimes employ provocation to advance a message that is often antisemitic, racist and xenophobic.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/11/nyregion/black-hebrew-israelites-jersey-city-suspects.html By Sarah Maslin Nir Dec. 12, 2019 The New York Times]</ref><ref>[https://apnews.com/9107f1204a15e4f5f67c8dcc9245f732 By Michael Kunzelman December 12, 2019 Associated Press]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe origins of the Black Hebrew Israelite movement are found in Frank Cherry and William Saunders Crowdy, who both claimed that they had revelations in which they believed that God told them that African Americans are descendants of the [[Hebrews]] in the [[Christian Bible]]; Cherry established the \"Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations\" in 1886 and Crowdy founded the \"[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]]\" in 1896.<ref name=\"Hutchinson2010\"/><ref name=\"Fernheimer2014\"/><ref name=\"IVSigler2009\"/><ref name=\"HSP1975\"/> The Church of God and Saints of Christ, originating in Kansas, retained elements of a messianic connection to [[Jesus]].<ref name=Chireau21>Chireau, p. 21.</ref>\n\nDuring the following decades, many more Black Hebrew congregations were established, with some holding no connection to Christianity. After World War I, for example, [[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]], an immigrant from [[Saint Kitts]], founded another Black Hebrew congregation in [[Harlem]], claiming descent from the ancient Israelites. He called it the \"[[Commandment Keepers]] of the Living God.\" <ref name=\"NYT090402\">{{cite news |first=Zev |last=Chafets |authorlink=Ze'ev Chafets |title=Obama's Rabbi |date=April 5, 2009 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/05/magazine/05rabbi-t.html |work =[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=December 28, 2016 }}</ref> Similar groups selected elements of Judaism and adapted them within a structure similar to that of the [[Black church]].<ref name=Chireau21/> He incorporated it in 1930 and moved the congregation to [[Brooklyn]], where he later founded the Israelite Rabbinical Seminary, where Black Hebrew rabbis have been educated and ordained.\n\n== Groups ==\nDuring the late 19th and early 20th centuries, dozens of Black Hebrew organizations were established.<ref name=Chireau21/> In Harlem alone, at least eight such groups were founded between 1919 and 1931.<ref name=Parfitt96>Parfitt, ''Judaising Movements'', p. 96.</ref> The Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations is the oldest-known Black Hebrew group<ref name=Singer57/> and the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] is one of the largest Black Hebrew organizations.<ref name=\"Africana\"/> The Commandment Keepers, founded by Wentworth Arthur Matthew in New York, are noted for their adherence to traditional Judaism.<ref name=Moses537/> The [[African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem]] are widely known for having moved from the United States, primarily Chicago, to Israel in the late 20th century.<ref name=Shipler/><ref name=Haas/><ref name=MFA/> Other Black Hebrew groups include the [[Israelite School of Universal Practical Knowledge]], based in Philadelphia, and the [[Nation of Yahweh]], based in Miami.\n\n=== Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations ===\nThe oldest known Black Hebrew organization is the [[Church of the Living God, the Pillar Ground of Truth for All Nations]].<ref name=Singer57>Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", p. 57.</ref><ref name=Chireau3031>Chireau, pp. 30\u201331. \"The founding dates of the earliest black-Jewish congregations are in dispute. Shapiro notes that F.S. Cherry's Church of God was organized in Tennessee in 1886, but other sources do not confirm this date. Another group, the Moorish Zion Temple, founded in 1899 by a Rabbi Richlieu of Brooklyn, New York, was one of the earliest black Jewish congregations that did not combine Jewish and Christian beliefs, as did the Church of God and the Saints of Christ.\"</ref> The group was founded by [[Frank Cherry]] in [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]], Tennessee, in 1886, and it later moved to [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=\"Singer57-58\">Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", pp. 57\u201358.</ref> Cherry, who was from the Deep South and had worked as a seaman and for the railroads before his ministry, taught himself Hebrew and [[Yiddish]].<ref>Parfitt, ''Black Jews in Africa and the Americas'', p. 88.</ref> Theologically, the Church of the Living God mixed elements of Judaism and Christianity, counting the Bible\u2014including the [[New Testament]]\u2014and the [[Talmud]] as essential scriptures.<ref name=Fauset34>Fauset, p. 34.</ref><ref name=Dorman73>Dorman, \"Black Israelites\", p. 73.</ref>\n\nThe rituals of Cherry's flock incorporated many Jewish practices and prohibitions alongside some Christian traditions.<ref name=\"Fauset36-40\">Fauset, pp. 36\u201340.</ref> For example, during prayer the men wore [[Kippah|skullcaps]] and congregants [[Mizrah|faced east]]. In addition, members of the Church were not permitted to eat [[pork]].<ref name=\"Fauset36-40\"/> Prayers were accompanied by musical instruments and [[Gospel music|gospel singing]].<ref name=\"Fauset36-37\">Fauset, pp. 36\u201337.</ref> Cherry died in 1963, when he was about 95 years old; his son, Prince Benjamin F. Cherry, succeeded him.<ref name=Dorman73/><ref name=Singer130>Singer, \"The Southern Origin of Black Judaism\", p. 130.</ref> Members of the church believed that he had temporarily left and would soon reappear in spirit in order to lead the church through his son.<ref name=Singer130/><ref name=\"Africana\">{{cite encyclopedia |last=Hudson |first=Peter |editor=[[Kwame Anthony Appiah]] |editor2=[[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]] |encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia Africana|Africana: The Encyclopedia of the African and African American Experience]] |title=Black Jews |year=1999 |publisher=Basic Civitas Books |location=New York |page=1050 }}</ref>\n\n=== Church of God and Saints of Christ ===\n{{Main|Church of God and Saints of Christ}}\n[[File:First Tabernacle - Washington, D.C..jpg|thumb|The former headquarters of the [[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] The building is now known as First Tabernacle Beth El and it is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].]]\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ was established in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]], Kansas, in 1896 by African-American [[William Saunders Crowdy]].<ref name=Fox>{{cite news|url=http://www.brown.edu/Students/INDY/archives/2005-09-29/articles/arts-fox_israelite.php |title=Sons of Abraham |accessdate=June 23, 2016 |last=Fox |first=Andrew |date=September 29, 2005 |work=[[The College Hill Independent]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060310213246/http://www.brown.edu/Students/INDY/archives/2005-09-29/articles/arts-fox_israelite.php |archivedate=March 10, 2006 }}</ref> The group established its headquarters in Philadelphia in 1899, and Crowdy later relocated to Washington, D.C., in 1903. After Crowdy's death in 1908, the church continued to grow under the leadership of William Henry Plummer, who moved the organization's headquarters to its permanent location in [[Belleville, Virginia|Belleville]], Virginia, in 1921.<ref name=\"Wynia31-34\">Wynia, pp. 31\u201334.</ref>\n\nIn 1936, the Church of God and Saints of Christ had more than 200 \"tabernacles\" (congregations) and 37,000 members.<ref name=\"Africana\"/><ref name=Wynia>Wynia, n.p. <!--introduction--></ref> [[Howard Z. Plummer|Howard Zebulun Plummer]] succeeded his father and became head of the organization in 1931.<ref>Greene, p. 42.</ref> His son, Levi Solomon Plummer, became the church's leader in 1975.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rlsp/ |title=Chief Rabbi Levi S. Plummer, G.F.A. |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> The Church of God and Saints of Christ was led by Rabbi Jehu A. Crowdy, Jr., a great-grandson of William Saunders Crowdy, from 2001 until his death in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rjac/ |title=Chief Rabbi Jehu A. Crowdy, Jr., G.F.A. |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> Since 2016, it has been led by Phillip E. McNeil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cogasoc.org/wordpress/leaders/rpem/ |title=Chief Rabbi Phillip E. McNeil |accessdate=January 1, 2018 |publisher=[[Church of God and Saints of Christ]] }}</ref> As of 2005, the church had fifty tabernacles in the United States and dozens more in Africa.<ref name=Fox/>\n\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ describes itself as \"the oldest African-American congregation in the United States that adheres to the tenets of Judaism\".<ref name=Chireau3031/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cogasoc.org/main.html |title=Church of God and Saints of Christ |accessdate=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080130002542/http://www.cogasoc.org/main.html |archivedate=January 30, 2008  }}</ref> Founded by American [[William Saunders Crowdy]] in Kansas in 1896, it teaches that all Jews were originally black, and that African Americans are descendants of the [[Ten Lost Tribes|lost tribes of Israel]].<ref name=Kidd>Kidd, p. 59.</ref><ref name=Singer59>Singer, \"Symbolic Identity Formation in an African American Religious Sect\", p. 59.</ref> Members believe that [[Jesus]] was neither God nor the son of God, but rather an adherent of Judaism and a [[prophet]]. They also consider William Saunders Crowdy, their founder in Kansas, to be a prophet.<ref name=\"gallagher\">Gallagher, p. 146.</ref>\n\nThe Church of God and Saints of Christ synthesizes rituals from both Judaism and Christianity. They have adopted rites drawn from both the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament]]s. Its Old Testament observances include the use of the [[Hebrew calendar|Jewish calendar]], the celebration of [[Passover]], the [[Brit milah|circumcision]] of infant males, the commemoration of the [[Shabbat|Sabbath]] on [[Saturday]], and the wearing of [[Kippah|yarmulkes]]. Its New Testament rites include [[baptism]] (immersion) and [[footwashing]], both of which have Old Testament origins.<ref name=Kidd/><ref name=Singer59/>\n\n=== Commandment Keepers ===\n{{Main|Commandment Keepers}}\n[[File:RabbiMatthewHoldingTorah.jpg|thumb|The founder of the Commandment Keepers, [[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]] holding a [[Sefer Torah]].]]\n[[Wentworth Arthur Matthew]] founded the Commandment Keepers Congregation in Harlem in 1919.<ref name=\"JVL\"/> Matthew was influenced by the non-black Jews he met as well as by [[Marcus Garvey]] and the [[Universal Negro Improvement Association and African Communities League]]. Garvey used the Biblical Jews in exile as a metaphor for [[black people]] in North America. One of the accomplishments of Garvey's movement was to strengthen the connection between black Americans and Africa, Ethiopia in particular. When Matthew later learned about the [[Beta Israel]]\u2014Ethiopian Jews\u2014he identified with them.<ref name=Chireau25>Chireau, p. 25.</ref>\n\nToday the Commandment Keepers follow traditional Jewish practices and observe [[Jewish holidays]].<ref name=Moses537>Moses, p. 537.</ref> Members observe [[kashrut]], circumcise newborn boys and celebrate [[Bar and Bat Mitzvah]]s, and their [[synagogue]] has a [[mechitza]] to separate men and women during worship.<ref name=\"Jewish Week\">{{cite news |first=Eric |last=Herschthal |title=Decline Of A Black Synagogue |url=http://joi.org/bloglinks/black%20synagogue%20Jewish%20Week.htm |work=[[The Jewish Week]] |date=July 6, 2007 |accessdate=February 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130112220712/http://joi.org/bloglinks/black%20synagogue%20Jewish%20Week.htm |archivedate=January 12, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nThe Commandment Keepers believe that they are descendants of [[Solomon]] and the [[Queen of Sheba]].<ref name=Parfitt95>Parfitt, ''Judaising Movements'', p. 95.</ref> Matthew taught that \"the Black man is a Jew\" and \"all genuine Jews are Black men\",<ref name=Sundquist116>Sundquist, p. 116.</ref> but he valued non-black Jews as those who had preserved Judaism over the centuries.<ref name=\"JVL\"/> Matthew maintained cordial ties with non-black Jewish leaders in New York and frequently invited them to worship at his synagogue.<ref name=Wolfson48>Wolfson, p. 48.</ref>\n\nMatthew established the Ethiopian Hebrew Rabbinical College (later renamed the Israelite Rabbinical Academy) in Brooklyn. He ordained more than 20 [[rabbi]]s, who went on to lead congregations throughout the United States and the Caribbean.<ref name=Sundquist116/><ref name=Wolfson48/> He remained the leader of the Commandment Keepers in Harlem, and in 1962 the congregation moved to a landmark building on 123rd Street.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyc-architecture.com/HAR/HAR025.htm |title=Commandment Keepers Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation |accessdate=February 1, 2008 |publisher=New York Architecture }}</ref>\n\nMatthew died in 1973, sparking an internal conflict over who would succeed him as head of the Harlem congregation. Shortly before his death, Matthew named his grandson, David Matthew Dor\u00e9, as the new spiritual leader. Dor\u00e9 was 16 years old at the time. In 1975, the synagogue's board elected Rabbi Willie White to be its leader. Rabbi Dor\u00e9 occasionally conducted services at the synagogue until the early 1980s, when White had Dor\u00e9 and some other members locked out of the building. Membership declined throughout the 1990s and by 2004, only a few dozen people belonged to the synagogue. In 2007 the Commandment Keepers sold the building, while various factions among former members sued one another.<ref name=\"Jewish Week\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackjews.org/Essays/DestructionofCommandmentKeepers.html |title=The Destruction of Commandment Keepers, Inc. 1919\u20132007 |accessdate=February 10, 2008 |last=Ben Levy |first=Sholomo |work=BlackJews.org |publisher=International Israelite Board of Rabbis }}</ref>\n\nBesides the Harlem group, there are eight or ten Commandment Keeper congregations in the New York area, and others exist throughout North America as well as in [[Israel]].<ref>Goldschmidt, p. 221.</ref> Since 2000, seven rabbis have graduated from the Israelite Rabbinical Academy founded by Matthew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blackjews.org/IsraeliteAcademy.html |title=Israelite Academy |accessdate=February 10, 2008 |work=BlackJews.org |publisher=International Israelite Board of Rabbis }}</ref>\n\n=== African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem ===\n{{Main|African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem}}\n[[File:Black hebrews Dimona visit1.jpg|thumb|African Hebrew Israelites speak to visitors in [[Dimona]], Israel.]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 32040 Africans Hebrew Israelites in Dimona.JPG|thumb|A sign in [[Dimona]].]]\n[[Ben Ammi Ben-Israel]] established the African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], in 1966, at a time when [[black nationalism]] was on the rise as a response to the [[Civil Rights Movement]]. In 1969, after a sojourn in [[Liberia]], Ben Ammi and about 30 Hebrew Israelites moved to [[Israel]].<ref name=Haas>{{cite news |last=Haas |first=Danielle |title=Black Hebrews fight for citizenship in Israel |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2002/11/15/MN144395.DTL |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=November 15, 2002 |accessdate=May 25, 2008 }}</ref> Over the next 20 years, nearly 600 more members left the United States for Israel. As of 2006, about 2,500 Hebrew Israelites live in [[Dimona]] and two other towns in the [[Negev]] region of Israel, where they are widely referred to as Black Hebrews.<ref name=CBS>{{cite news |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Music Earns Black Hebrews Some Acceptance |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/05/ap/world/mainD8GPUNGG8.shtml |work=[[CBS News]] |date=April 5, 2006 |accessdate=May 25, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060507212849/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/05/ap/world/mainD8GPUNGG8.shtml |archivedate = May 7, 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> In addition, there are Hebrew Israelite communities in several major American cities, including Chicago, St. Louis, and Washington, D.C.<ref name=Michaeli75>Michaeli, p. 75.</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrews believe they are descended from members of the [[Tribe of Judah]] who were exiled from the [[Land of Israel]] after the [[Roman Empire|Romans]] destroyed the [[Second Temple]] in 70 CE.<ref name=CBS/><ref name=OurStory>{{cite web |url=http://www.kingdomofyah.com/our_story.htm |title=Our Story |accessdate=May 25, 2008 |publisher=The African Hebrew Israelites of Jerusalem }}</ref> The group incorporates elements of [[African-American culture]] into their interpretation of the Bible.<ref name=Michaeli75/> They do not recognize rabbinical Jewish interpretations such as the [[Talmud]].<ref name=CBS/> The Black Hebrews observe [[Shabbat]] and biblically ordained [[Jewish holidays]] such as [[Yom Kippur]] and [[Passover]].<ref name=Michaeli76>Michaeli, p. 76.</ref>\n\nMen wear ''[[tzitzit]]'' on their African print shirts, women follow the [[niddah]] (biblical laws concerning menstruation),<ref name=Michaeli75/> and newborn boys are circumcised.<ref name=Haas/> In accordance with their interpretation of the Bible, the Black Hebrews follow a strictly [[veganism|vegan diet]] and only wear [[natural fabric]]s.<ref name=Haas/><ref name=OurStory/> Most men have [[Polygyny|more than one wife]], and [[birth control]] is not permitted.<ref name=CBS/>\n\nWhen the first Black Hebrews arrived in Israel in 1969, they claimed citizenship under the [[Law of Return]], which gives eligible Jews immediate citizenship.<ref>Michaeli, pp. 73\u201374.</ref> The Israeli government ruled in 1973 that the group did not qualify for automatic citizenship because they could not prove Jewish descent and had not undergone Orthodox conversion. The Black Hebrews were denied [[work permit]]s and state benefits. The group accused the Israeli government of [[racism|racist discrimination]].<ref name=Michaeli74>Michaeli, p. 74.</ref> In 1981, a group of American civil rights activists led by [[Bayard Rustin]] investigated and concluded that racism was not the cause of the Black Hebrews' situation.<ref name=Shipler>{{cite news |last=Shipler |first=David K. |title=Israelis Urged To Act Over Black Hebrew Cult |url=https://select.nytimes.com/search/restricted/article?res=F4071FFA395F0C738FDDA80894D9484D81 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 30, 1981 |accessdate=May 28, 2008 }}</ref> No official action was taken to return the Black Hebrews to the United States, but some individual members were [[Deportation|deported]] for working illegally.<ref name=Michaeli74/>\n\nSome Black Hebrews [[relinquishment of United States nationality|renounced their American citizenship]] in order to try to prevent more deportations. In 1990, Illinois legislators helped negotiate an agreement that resolved the Black Hebrews' legal status in Israel. Members of the group are permitted to work and they also have access to housing and social services. The Black Hebrews reclaimed their American citizenship and have received aid from the U.S. government, which helped them build a school and additional housing.<ref name=Michaeli74/> In 2003 the agreement was revised, and the Black Hebrews were granted [[permanent residency]] in Israel.<ref name=MFA>{{cite web|url=http://mfa.gov.il/MFA/AboutIsrael/People/Pages/The%20Black%20Hebrews.aspx |title=The Hebrew Israelite Community |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |date=September 29, 2006 |publisher=Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs }}</ref><ref name=Kaufman>{{cite news |last=Kaufman |first=David |title=Quest for a Homeland Gains a World Stage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/16/fashion/sundaystyles/16BUTLER.html |work=The New York Times|date=April 16, 2006 |accessdate=May 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Elyakim Ben-Israel became the first Black Hebrew to gain Israeli citizenship. The Israeli government said that more Black Hebrews may be granted citizenship.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alush |first=Zvi |title=First Black Hebrew Gets Israeli Citizenship |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3665976,00.html |work=[[Ynetnews]] |date=February 2, 2009 |accessdate=February 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrews of Israel maintain a [[gospel music|gospel choir]], which tours throughout Israel and the United States. The group owns restaurants in several Israeli cities.<ref name=Michaeli74/> In 2003 the Black Hebrews garnered public attention when singer [[Whitney Houston]] visited them in Dimona.<ref>{{cite news |title=Israel retreat for Houston |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/2940042.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=May 27, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Whitney Houston visits Israel for Christmas album inspiration |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2003-05-27-houston-israel_x.htm |work=USA Today|date=May 28, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Palti |first=Michal |title=Whitney does Dimona |url=http://www.culteducation.com/reference/black_hebrews/black_hebrews6.html |work=[[Haaretz]] |date=May 29, 2003 |accessdate=May 26, 2008 }}</ref> In 2006, [[Eddie Butler (singer)|Eddie Butler]], a Black Hebrew, was chosen by the Israeli public to [[Israel in the Eurovision Song Contest 2006|represent Israel]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006|Eurovision Song Contest]].<ref name=CBS/><ref name=Kaufman/>\n\n== Extremist fringe ==\nIn late 2008, the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) wrote that \"the extremist fringe of the Hebrew Israelite movement\" is [[Black supremacy|black supremacist]]. It also wrote that the members of such groups \"believe that [[Jews]] are devilish impostors and ... openly condemn [[White people|whites]] as [[evil]] personified, deserving only death or slavery\". The SPLC also wrote that \"most Hebrew Israelites are neither explicitly racist nor [[Antisemitism|anti-Semitic]] and do not advocate violence\".<ref name=Ready>{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2008/racist-black-hebrew-israelites-becoming-more-militant |title=Racist Black Hebrew Israelites Becoming More Militant |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |date=Fall 2008 |work=Intelligence Report |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center }}</ref>\n\nThe Black Hebrew groups which are characterized as black supremacist by the SPLC include the [[Israelite School of Universal Practical Knowledge]],<ref name=\"god_and_general\">{{cite news|url=http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=948|title=God and the General. Leader Discusses Black Supremacist Group|date=Fall 2008|work=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|accessdate=September 8, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907052245/http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=948|archive-date=September 7, 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[Nation of Yahweh]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.splcenter.org/get-informed/intelligence-report/browse-all-issues/2001/winter/popularity-and-populism |title=Popularity and Populism |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |first=Martin A. |last=Lee |date=Winter 2001 |work=Intelligence Report |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center}}</ref> and the [[Israelite Church of God in Jesus Christ]].<ref name=Ready/> Also, the [[Anti-Defamation League]] has written that the \"12 Tribes of Israel\" website, which is maintained by a Black Hebrew group, promotes black supremacy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.adl.org/poisoning_web/black_bigots.html |title=Poisoning the Web: Hatred Online \u2013 African-American Anti-Semitism |accessdate=November 5, 2016 |year=2001 |publisher=Anti-Defamation League|url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102103308/http://archive.adl.org/poisoning_web/black_bigots.html |archivedate=January 2, 2014  }}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2019, the Southern Poverty Law Center \"lists 144 Black Hebrew Israelite organizations as black separatist hate groups because of their antisemitic and anti-white beliefs.\"<ref name=\"splc201912\">{{cite web |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2019/12/12/suspects-jersey-city-attack-expressed-interest-black-hebrew-israelites-authorities-say |title=Suspects in Jersey City Attack 'Expressed Interest' in Black Hebrew Israelites, Authorities Say |last= |first= |date=December 12, 2019 |website= |publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>{{Context-inline|date=January 2020}}\n\nA 1999 [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] [[Project Megiddo|terrorism risk assessment report]] stated that \"violent radical fringe members\" of the Black Hebrew Israelite movement hold \"beliefs [that] bear a striking resemblance to the [[Christian Identity]] theology practiced by many [[White supremacy|white supremacists]].\"<ref name=Megidddo>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbi.gov:80/library/megiddo/publicmegiddo.pdf |title=Project Megiddo |date=1999 |publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000815061728/http://www.fbi.gov/library/megiddo/publicmegiddo.pdf |pages=23\u201325 |archivedate=August 15, 2000 |accessdate=May 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Nacos2015\">{{cite book |last=Nacos |first=Brigitte L. |title=Terrorism and Counterterrorism |year=2015 |publisher=Routledge |location= |isbn=9781317343646 |page=79}}</ref> It also wrote that \"the overwhelming majority of [Black Hebrew Israelites] are unlikely to engage in violence.\"<ref name=Megidddo/>\n\nOn December 10, 2019, two people who had expressed interest in the Black Hebrew Israelite movement, were killed in a [[2019 Jersey City shooting|shootout with police]] after killing a police detective at [[Bayview \u2013 New York Bay Cemetery|Bayview Cemetery]] and three people at the JC Kosher Supermarket in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], New Jersey; the Jewish co-owner of the grocery store, an employee, and a Jewish shopper. Authorities treated the incident as an act of [[Domestic terrorism in the United States|domestic terrorism]].<ref name=WaPoJersey>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/15/probe-jersey-city-shooting-leads-fbi-arrest-pawn-shop-owner-weapons-charges/|title=Probe of Jersey City shooting leads FBI to arrest pawn shop owner on weapons charge|author=Derek Hawkins|work=The Washington Post|date=December 15, 2019}}</ref> [[Capers Funnye]], who has been the [[rabbi]] for the past 26 years of the 200-member [[Beth Shalom B'nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation]],<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/05/magazine/05rabbi-t.html?mtrref=www.google.com&gwh=8160E532FBE361FE2D084D04F6C16C31&gwt=pay&assetType=REGIWALL By Zev Chafets for the New York Times, Barack Obama's Rabbi - Capers Funnye - Profile \"Funnye, the chief rabbi of the Beth Shalom B\u2019nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation in Chicago\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/commentary/ct-opinion-anti-semitism-rabbi-funnye-black-hebrew-israelites-20191213-mjv6q5azvrf63pyuqpkqalhc2i-story.html By Julia Lieblich for the Chicago Tribune Dec. 13, 2019 \"Commentary: Rabbi Capers Funnye, other Black Hebrew Israelites wrongly connected to Jersey City shooters\", \"'I felt terrible that innocent lives were taken first and foremost,' said Funnye, rabbi for 26 years of the 200-member Beth Shalom B\u2019nai Zaken Ethiopian Hebrew Congregation of Chicago, a member of the Chicago Board of Rabbis and the chief rabbi of the International Israelite Board of Rabbis.\"]</ref> condemned the attack and said that his community was \"gripped by sadness\" over \"the heinous actions of two disturbed individuals who cloaked themselves in anti-Semitism and hate-filled rhetoric\". He also criticized the media reports by saying that it was \"unfortunate that the media uses the term \u2018Black Hebrew Israelites\u2019 without distinction as if the description is a one size fits all and it is absolutely not!\" Funnye emphasized that \"we don\u2019t want to be seen as some radical fringe group with a false narrative because we are black and profess Judaism; we are Torah-oriented Jews.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/black-hebrew-israelite-leader-condemns-heinous-jersey-city-shooting/|title=Black Hebrew Israelite leader condemns \u2018heinous\u2019 Jersey City shooting|last=JTA|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-22}}</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2019, a man with a [[machete]] [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|attacked several Orthodox Jewish people]] during [[Hanukkah]] celebrations in a house in [[Monsey, New York|Monsey]], New York. Authorities revealed the fact that his journals included what appeared to be a reference to Black Hebrew Israelites stating that \"Hebrew Israelites\" have taken from \"ebinoid Israelites\".<ref name=WaPoNY>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/30/monsey-stabbing-grafton-thomas-suspect/|title=Hanukkah stabbing suspect searched \u2018why did Hitler hate the Jews,\u2019 prosecutors say|date=December 30, 2019|author=Shayna Jacobs, Deanna Paul, Maria Sacchetti and Hannah Knowles|work=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of theological and historical claims ==\nAfrican American [[Christian apologetics]] organizations, such as the Jude 3 Project, have critiqued the theological and historical claims presented by various Black Hebrew Israelite sects.<ref name=\"Lee\">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Morgan |title=The Hebrew Israelites in That March for Life Viral Video, Explained |url=https://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2019/january-web-only/hebrew-israelites-urban-apologetics-covington-march-life.html |publisher=[[Christianity Today]] |accessdate=2 February 2020 |language=English |date=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States}}\n* [[African American\u2013Jewish relations]]\n* [[Afro-American religion]]\n* [[Groups claiming affiliation with Israelites]]\n** [[British Israelism]]\n** [[Christian Identity]]\n** [[French Israelism]]\n** [[Nordic Israelism]]\n* [[Messianic Judaism]]\n* [[Moorish Science Temple of America]]\n* [[Religion in Black America]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite book |last=Ben-Jochannan |first=Yosef A.A. |authorlink=Yosef Ben-Jochannan |title=We, the Black Jews: Witness to the \"White Jewish Race\" Myth |origyear=1983 |year=1993 |publisher=Black Classic Press |location=Baltimore |isbn=0-933121-40-7 }}\n*{{cite book |first1=Edith |last1=Bruder |authorlink1=Edith Bruder |first2=Tudor |last2=Parfitt |authorlink2=Tudor Parfitt |editor=Edith Bruder |editor2=Tudor Parfitt |title=African Zion: Studies in Black Judaism |year=2012 |publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |isbn=978-1-4438-3802-3 |chapter=Introduction |chapterurl=http://www.cambridgescholars.com/download/sample/57725 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Chireau |first=Yvonne |editor=Yvonne Patricia Chireau |editor2=[[Nathaniel Deutsch]] |title=Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-511257-1 |chapter=Black Culture and Black Zion: African American Religious Encounters with Judaism, 1790\u20131930, an Overview |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780195112580 }}\n* {{cite book |editor-last1=Gallagher |editor-first1=Eugene V. |editor-last2=Ashcraft |editor-first2=W. Michael |title=Introduction to New and Alternative Religions in America |volume=1 |year=2006 |publisher=Greenwood Press |location=Westport, Conn. |isbn=0-275-98713-2 |last=Dorman |first=Jacob S. |chapter=Black Israelites }}\n* {{cite book |last=Fauset |first=Arthur Huff |authorlink=Arthur 